I. Introduction
Objective:
The objective of this proposal is to outline a comprehensive strategy for adopting web
development practices at the Wisconsin Maritime Museum, focusing on ensuring accessibility
for all users. This strategy aims to make the museum's online presence inclusive, ensuring that
it meets WCAG 2.0 or 2.1 AA standards and offers an equitable experience for every visitor,
regardless of ability.
Context:
Web accessibility is not merely a technical requirement; it is a fundamental aspect of ensuring
that digital spaces are open and inclusive to all. According to the World Health Organization,
over 1 billion people, or 15% of the world's population, experience some form of disability.
Despite this, a significant portion of the web remains inaccessible to these individuals. The
museum sector is no exceptionstudies show that many museum websites fail to meet basic
accessibility standards, thereby excluding a substantial audience. This proposal addresses the
need for accessible web development at the Wisconsin Maritime Museum, focusing on creating
an inclusive digital environment that reflects the museum's commitment to public education and
historical preservation.
Group:
Our proposals will be addressing potential technology adoptions and critical oversight on the
museums digital collections database. We will specifically be working with the Carus Collection,
a collection of photographs and ephemera from ship captain Edward Carus. Our group-wide
proposal is addressing potential technological tools and workflows that would benefit or build on
the current digital collection. Overall, we believe that while the database is a fantastic resource
given the limitations of the museum, there are some simple, yet effective ways it can be
improved using the tools we have acquired through this class. Specifically, we as a group wish
to target tools and workflows that may better assist researchers and archivists in better
understanding and utilizing the data within the online collection. These tools can be used for a
variety of purposes, such as research topic generation, historical mapping, education, and data
visualization.
II. Institutional Overview
Institution Description:
The Wisconsin Maritime Museum, located in Manitowoc, Wisconsin, is a premier institution
dedicated to preserving and interpreting the maritime history of the Great Lakes. Founded in
1970, the museum houses a vast collection of artifacts, including ship models, historical
documents, and the World War II submarine USS Cobia. The museum's mission is to engage
the public with the rich maritime heritage of the region, offering educational programs,
interactive exhibits, and research opportunities.
Users and Stakeholders:
The museum's stakeholders encompass a diverse group of users, each with distinct needs and
expectations. Understanding these user groups is critical to developing a website that meets
their varied requirements:
General Public Users:
This group includes tourists, local visitors, and casual learners who seek an engaging,
visually appealing experience. Their needs revolve around easy navigation, compelling
content, and interactive features that bring maritime history to life. These users may not
have a deep understanding of maritime history but are eager to explore and learn
through the museums offerings.
Academic Researchers and Librarians:
These users require detailed, accurate access to the museum's collections and archives.
Their needs include advanced search capabilities, metadata-rich content, and access to
high-resolution images and documents. Researchers may also seek to download
datasets or use geospatial information to analyze historical maritime routes and events.
Educators and Students:
This group looks for educational resources that align with curriculum standards. They
need access to multimedia content, downloadable lesson plans, and interactive tools
that facilitate learning about maritime history.
Information and Technology Needs:
The museum's information needs are centered around showcasing its exhibits, providing
educational resources, and engaging a broad audience. The technological needs include a
robust, accessible website that serves as a digital extension of the museum. The website must
handle various data types, including text, images, videos, and interactive elements, while
ensuring that all content is accessible to users with disabilities.
Representation of Institutional Data Types:
The museum's collections include a wide range of data types, such as artifact metadata,
historical documents, photographs, and geospatial data. Effective representation of these data
types on the website is crucial for accessibility. For example, the museum might use interactive
maps to display shipwreck locations, overlaid with historical data about each event. Additionally,
the website could feature virtual tours of the museum, allowing users to explore exhibits from
their devices. These features must be designed with accessibility in mind, ensuring that all users
can engage with the content regardless of their abilities.
III. Technology Overview (Individual And Group)
Description of Web Development Tools:
The website will be developed using a combination of HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, with web
frameworks such as Bootstrap for UI/UX design and ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet
Applications) to enhance accessibility. Additionally, the use of WebGL for 3D graphics and
Leaflet for interactive maps will be explored to create a dynamic and immersive experience.

Potential Implementation:
The website will be built with accessibility as a core principle from the ground up. This includes
the following features:
Interactive Geospatial Data:
Using Leaflet, Kalila in our group will feature interactive maps that allow users to explore
maritime routes, shipwrecks, and other historical events. These maps will be accessible,
offering keyboard navigation and alternative text descriptions for all interactive elements.
3D Models and Virtual Tours:
Leveraging WebGL, the site will include 3D models of artifacts, such as the USS Cobia,
and virtual tours of the museum. These features will be complemented with descriptive
audio and text alternatives to ensure accessibility for users with visual impairments.
Functionality and Benefits:
The chosen technologies and design approach will ensure that the website is not only functional
and visually appealing but also accessible to users with disabilities. By prioritizing accessibility,
the museum will broaden its reach, allowing more people to engage with its content. Moreover,
this approach will set a new standard for accessibility in the museum sector, positioning the
Wisconsin Maritime Museum as a leader in digital inclusivity.
IV. The Why
Informative Aspect:
Accessible web development is essential for creating an inclusive digital environment. For many
users, particularly those with disabilities, an inaccessible website can be a significant barrier to
engaging with content. In the context of museums, this means that valuable educational and
cultural resources may be out of reach for a significant portion of the population. By
implementing accessible web development practices, the Wisconsin Maritime Museum can
ensure that all users, regardless of ability, can access and interact with its online content. This
not only aligns with legal standards but also fulfills the museums mission to educate and
engage a diverse audience.
Persuasive Aspect:
Adopting accessible web development practices will position the museum as a leader in
inclusivity and digital accessibility. This leadership role can enhance the museums reputation,
attract more visitors, and potentially open up new opportunities for partnerships and funding.
Moreover, an accessible website can improve overall visitor satisfaction, leading to increased
engagement and repeat visits. A study by the Nielsen Norman Group found that accessible
websites often provide a better user experience for all users, not just those with disabilities. By
making accessibility a priority, the museum can ensure that it provides the best possible
experience for every visitor.
Case Study:
Consider the example of the Smithsonian National Museum of Natural History, which
implemented a comprehensive accessibility initiative for its digital content. The museums
website now includes features such as audio descriptions, keyboard navigation, and alternative
text for images. As a result, the Smithsonian saw a significant increase in engagement from
users with disabilities, as well as positive feedback from all user groups. This case
demonstrates the tangible benefits of prioritizing accessibility in web development.
V. Code And Power
Identification of Biases:
Biases in web development can manifest in various ways, from the choice of content to the
design of user interfaces. At the Wisconsin Maritime Museum, potential biases might include the
prioritization of certain historical narratives over others or the presentation of data in ways that
are inaccessible to some users. For example, non-semantic HTML elements can create barriers
for screen reader users, while certain data visualizations might inadvertently emphasize
information that aligns with the museums institutional perspective, potentially marginalizing
alternative narratives.
Impact on Stakeholders:
These biases can disproportionately affect users with disabilities, preventing them from fully
engaging with the museums digital content. For instance, if a data visualization is not
accessible to screen readers, users with visual impairments may be unable to access critical
information. Similarly, if the website prioritizes certain narratives, it may alienate users who are
interested in exploring different aspects of maritime history. This can lead to exclusion and
marginalization, undermining the museums mission to provide an inclusive and educational
experience for all.
Theoretical Considerations:
From a theoretical standpoint, biases in web development reflect broader societal inequities.
Critical theory, particularly the work of scholars like Michel Foucault, emphasizes the ways in
which power dynamics shape knowledge production and dissemination. In the context of the
Wisconsin Maritime Museum, this means that the design and content of the website must be
carefully considered to avoid reinforcing existing power structures and to promote equity and
inclusion. This involves not only making the website accessible but also ensuring that the
content is representative of diverse perspectives and that all users have the opportunity to
engage with the museums digital offerings.
VI. Ethical Web Development Strategies
Bias Mitigation:
To mitigate biases, the website will adhere to the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG)
2.1 AA standards. This includes using semantic HTML, providing text alternatives for non-text
content, and ensuring keyboard accessibility. Additionally, the museum will engage in inclusive
design practices, such as conducting stakeholder consultations and usability testing with diverse
user groups. These practices will help identify potential biases and ensure that the website
meets the needs of all users.
Accessibility Testing:
Accessibility testing will be an ongoing process throughout the websites development. Tools
such as Axe Accessibility Checker and WAVE will be used to identify and rectify accessibility
issues. These tools provide detailed reports on potential problems, such as missing alt text or
insufficient color contrast, allowing the development team to make necessary adjustments.
Additionally, the museum will conduct user testing with individuals who have disabilities,
ensuring that the website is truly accessible in real-world scenarios.
VII. The Space between the Code
User Experience (UX) Considerations:
User experience (UX) is closely intertwined with accessibility. A well-designed website not only
meets accessibility standards but also provides an intuitive and enjoyable experience for all
users. To achieve this, the website will incorporate UX design principles such as simplicity,
consistency, and user control. For example, the navigation will be designed to be easy to
understand and use, with clear labels and logical groupings of content. Additionally, the website
will include features such as adjustable font sizes and color contrast settings, allowing users to
customize the interface to their needs.

html
Copy code
<button onclick="textToSpeech('Welcome to the Wisconsin Maritime
Museum')">Play Welcome Message</button>
<script>
function textToSpeech(text) {
var msg = new SpeechSynthesisUtterance(text);
window.speechSynthesis.speak(msg);
}
</script>
This JavaScript function enables text-to-speech, making the website more accessible to users
with reading disabilities or visual impairments.
Analysis and Output:
The accessibility features implemented on the website will be analyzed through user testing and
feedback. For instance, user interaction data will be collected to assess the effectiveness of
keyboard navigation and screen reader compatibility. The results of these tests will be
documented and used to make further improvements to the website.
Accessibility Compliance Evidence:
To demonstrate compliance with WCAG 2.1 AA standards, the website will undergo thorough
testing using tools such as WAVE and Axe Accessibility Checker. The following WAVE report
shows that the homepage contains no accessibility errors, providing evidence that the website
meets the required standards.
